{{Infobox video game |image=Davis Cup Tennis Coverart.jpeg |developer=[[Hokus Pokus Games]] |publisher=[[Ubisoft]] |platforms=[[TurboGrafx-16]] [[Game Boy Advance]] |released='''TurboGrafx-16''' {{vgrelease|NA|1991}} '''Game Boy Advance'''{{vgrelease|NA|October 15, 2002}} |genre=[[Sports game|Sports]] |modes=[[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]] }}
'''''Davis Cup Tennis''''' is a [[sports game]] developed by [[Loriciel]] in 1991 for the [[TurboGrafx-16]] and then by [[Hokus Pokus Games]] and published by [[Ubisoft]] for the [[Game Boy Advance]]. It was released in the United States in 1991 on the TurboGrafx-16 and again for the [[Game Boy Advance]] on October 15, 2002. It is the North American port of [[Tennis Cup]], previously released in 1989 on micro-computers.
In the GBA version's two [[game mode]]s, the player assumes control of either a [[tennis]] player during a single match or an entire country's team in the [[Davis Cup]], an international competition. [[Multiplayer]] is supported through the [[Game Link Cable|link cable]]. The game garnered mixed reviews from critics, who overall felt that it paled in comparison to 2002's ''[[Virtua Tennis]]'' and earlier versions of ''[[Mario Tennis]]''.
==Gameplay== The game follows the rules of [[tennis]] closely. Each [[tennis match|match]] has a minimum of 5 sets by default.<ref name="GameSpy"></ref> Players are able to control the difficulty of the [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|AI]] before starting their game as well.<ref name="GameSpy" /> The player can either choose to play a "Quick Play" mode which allows for a single tennis match, or to play through the full [[Davis Cup]], where the player must choose the team captain and compete through the entire tournament with the rotating player rotation.<ref name="GameSpy" />
The tennis players are represented by [[two-dimensional]] [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]], while the [[tennis court|court]] is given the illusion of being [[3D computer graphics|three-dimensional]].<ref name="GS"></ref> Players are able to control the power of their initial serve, but cannot control how hard they hit balls already in play.<ref name="GameSpy" />
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | title = Reception | MC = 59/100<ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web |title=Davis Cup Tennis for Game Boy Advance Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/davis-cup-tennis |accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> | GSpy = 80/100<ref name="GameSpy">{{cite web |title=GameSpy: Davis Cup Tennis |author=Fryman, Avi |date=November 6, 2002 |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |url=http://www.gamespy.com/reviews/december02/daviscuptennisgba/index.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030423073416/http://www.gamespy.com/reviews/december02/daviscuptennisgba/index.shtml |archivedate=April 23, 2003 |deadurl=yes |accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> | GameZone = 7 of 10<ref name="GameZone">{{cite web |title=Davis Cup Tennis - GBA - Review |author=Code Cowboy |date=November 12, 2002 |publisher=GameZone |url=http://gameboy.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20785_GBA.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021119105322/http://gameboy.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r20785_GBA.htm |archivedate=November 19, 2002 |deadurl=no |accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> | IGN = 5 of 10<ref name="IGN">{{cite web |title=Davis Cup Tennis |author=Harris, Craig |date=October 24, 2002|publisher=[[IGN]] |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/10/24/davis-cup-tennis |accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> | GSpot = 6.3 of 10<ref name="GS">{{cite web |title=Davis Cup Tennis Review |author=Provo, Frank |date=January 3, 2003 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/davis-cup-tennis-review/1900-2907905/ |publisher=[[GameSpot]] | accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> }}
''Davis Cup Tennis'' garnered mixed reviews from gaming press, who felt that the game was lackluster compared to ''[[Virtua Tennis]]''. [[GameSpot]]'s Frank Provo and [[IGN]]'s Craig Harris both criticized the lack of an in-game save option that you could activate during your match, with Craig Harris remarking that the design "isn't exactly handheld friendly".<ref name="GS" /><ref name="IGN" /> Frank Provo felt that the larger variety of techniques found in ''Virtua Tennis'' made it "the better option".<ref name="GS" /> [[GameSpy]]'s Avi Fryman remarked on the game's averageness in comparison to its competitors, commenting "... if all available copies of ''Virtua Tennis'' and ''Mario Tennis'' suddenly vaporized, there might be a reason for casual gamers to pick this one up."<ref name="GameSpy" />
