sic of Haiti| Haitian]] and [[Music of the Dominican Republic|Dominican folk music]], and her cultural preservation projects has raised awareness of the significance of the [[Samaná Americans|Samaná Americanos' enclave]].
==Education and early work== Davis received her B.A. (Magna Cum Laude) in [[Anthropology]] from the [[University of California]] and a Ph.D. from the [[University of Illinois]]. Her graduate field work took her to various Caribbean islands, of which she has published,<ref name="Back Matter">{{cite journal | url=https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B_q6VhhkczIYS1o2UkR6T3dKS2s | title=Back Matter | author=The Editors | journal=Ethnomusicology| date=January 1972 | volume=16 | issue=1 | pages=16}}</ref> but it was in the [[Dominican Republic]] where early on in her graduate career she established her reputation as an [[Iconoclasm|iconoclast]], [[Cultural critic|critic]] and dedicated scholar to [[Afro-Caribbean|Black culture]]. In 1972, she arrived at the island of [[Hispaniola]] with the suspicion that [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominicans]] owned more to the [[Afro-Caribbean]] culture than what had been documented yet. In an article published in a leading [[Listín Diario|Dominican newspaper]], Xiomarita Perez wrote candidly about Davis' style and links to the country: "Martha works from the heart and with the heart... Her job is essential to the country's social memory" ([[Spanish Language|Spanish]]:«Martha trabaja de corazón y con el corazón... Su oficio es delicado e importante para la memoria social del país»).<ref name="Folcloreadno">{{cite news | url=http://www.listindiario.com/la-vida/2012/10/31/253129/martha-ellen-davis | title=Folcloreadno: Martha Ellen Davis |publisher= Listín Diario| date=October 31, 2012 | accessdate=December 23, 2015 | author=Pérez, Xiomarita}}</ref>
==Institutional involvement==
Part of Davis' legacy includes co-founding the Committee of Applied Ethnomusicology within the [[Society for Ethnomusicology]] in 1998,<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eo1yCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA27&lpg=PA27&dq=Committee+of+%22Applied+Ethnomusicology%22+Martha+Ellen+Davis&source=bl&ots=LO4s-JQju3&sig=Qizrc83UciqZWQCLNRwTZFpJ_GM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2nbGW1_TJAhWJJx4KHX9UAO4Q6AEIMDAD#v=onepage&q=Committee%20of%20%22Applied%20Ethnomusicology%22%20Martha%20Ellen%20Davis&f=false | title=The Oxford Handbook of Applied Ethnomusicology | publisher=Oxford University Press | author=Todd Titon, Jeff | year=2015 | location=Oxford | pages=27 | isbn=0199351708}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ethnomusicology.org/?Groups_SectionsAE | title=Applied Ethnomusicology Section | publisher=Society of Ethnomusicology | accessdate=December 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://library.brown.edu/cds/invested_in_community/bios.html | title=Invested in Community: Ethnomusicology and Musical Advocacy | publisher=Brown University Library Center for Digital Scholarship | accessdate=December 23, 2015}}</ref> writing four seminal books,<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/28668246| title=La otra ciencia: el vodú dominicano como religión y medicina populares | publisher=Editora Universitaria (UASD) | author=Davis, Martha | year=1987 | location=Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic}}</ref> producing documentaries,<ref>{{cite journal | jstor=20174439 | title=Film and Video Reviews | journal=Ethnomusicology | year=2006 | volume=50 | issue=1 | pages=172}}</ref> and writing numerous scientific articles. She has been considered an authority in [[Afro-Caribbean music]] and is quoted extensively in the literature. Davis' book, ''La otra ciencia'', earned the National Nonfiction Award of the Dominican Republic. While continuing as an affiliate professor at the University of Florida, since ca. 2003 Davis has spent most of her time in the Dominican Republic as honorary researcher of the Museo del Hombre Dominicano (Museum of the Dominican Man) and oral-history expert and researcher of the Archivo General de la Nación (The National Archives), offering lectures, advising young scholars, and writing. In November 1, 2012, the Museo celebrated her 40 years of research in the country.<ref name="Celebración">{{cite web | url=https://rossydiaz.wordpress.com/2012/10/30/celebracion-a-etnomusicologa-martha-ellen-davis/ | title=Celebración a etnomusicóloga Martha Ellen Davis | publisher=Museo del Hombre Dominicano | work=Blog | date=October 15, 2012 | accessdate=December 23, 2015 | author=Díaz, Rossy}}</ref>
==Scholarly contributions== Davis' long-standing interest in the Dominican and Haitian cultures derives from her belief that "The island of Hispaniola—the Spanish colony of Santo Domingo and first colony in the New World—was the initial diasporal crucible and cultural bridge of [[the Americas]]."<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B_q6VhhkczIYUzEzS0xickl4TEE | title=Diasporal Dimensions of Dominican Folk Religion and Music | author=Davis, Martha Ellen | journal=Black Music Research Journal | year=2012 | volume=32 | issue=1 | pages=161–191}}</ref> In 1976, Davis, who rivals [[Fernando Ortiz Fernández|Fernando Ortiz]] in years of research into Afro-Caribbean culture, challenged the Dominican cultural establishment. According to Peter Manuel from [[CUNY]], she convincingly suggested "that if there is any rightful ‘national’ music of the Dominican Republic, it would be not the [[Merengue music|Merengue]], with its specifically regional origin in the [[Cibao]], but rather the various types of ''salve'', which have flourished throughout the country."<ref>{{cite journal | title=El Merengue: Musica y Baile de la Republica Dominicana, and: El Merengue en la Cultura Dominicana y del Caribe: Memorias del Primer Congreso Internacional "Musica, Identidad, y Cultura en el Caribe" | author=Manuel, Peter | journal=Latin American Music Review | year=2007 | volume=28 | issue=1 | pages=172 | doi=10.1353/lat.2007.0020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | jstor=41348253 | title=El origen de sones afroantillanos: perspectivas dominicanas con respecto a "Son de la Ma' Teodora" | author=Bars, Karoline | journal=Latin American Music Review | year=2011 | volume=32 | issue=2 | pages=233}}</ref> Her work has also crossed into the realm of religion, and here she also suggested that what is commonly called Dominican "Folk Religion" is more accurately described as folk Catholicism of which one component is "Dominican [[Dominican Vudú|Vodou]]."<ref>{{cite book | title=Sites and politics of religious diversity in southern Europe: the best of all gods | publisher=Brill | author=Mapril, Jose | year=2013 | pages=39 | isbn=90-04-25523-0}}</ref>
